I now have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Let me compile this into a comprehensive design plan.

---

## Turn View Implementation Plan

### 1. Data Structures

#### 1.1. `DetailViewMode` enum (in `app.rs`)

Add alongside the existing `TaskViewMode`:

```rust
/// How the session detail timeline is displayed.
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub enum DetailViewMode {
    /// Linear timeline (current behavior) — all events in a scrolled list.
    Linear,
    /// Turn-based side-by-side — left: user prompt, right: agent response.
    Turn,
}
```

#### 1.2. `Turn` struct (in `app.rs` or a new `turn.rs` module)

This is a lightweight computed struct that references indices into the visible events list. It should NOT own event data -- it is rebuilt on every render from the current `DisplayEvent` list.

```rust
/// A conversational turn: one user prompt and the agent's full response.
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct Turn {
    /// Index range into the visible events Vec for the user prompt(s).
    /// Typically a single UserMessage, but could include SystemMessage events
    /// that arrive between the previous agent block and this user message.
    pub user_event_indices: Vec<usize>,

    /// Index range into the visible events Vec for agent response events.
    /// Includes AgentMessage, Thinking, ToolCall, ToolResult, FileEdit,
    /// TaskStart/TaskEnd, etc. -- everything until the next UserMessage.
    pub agent_event_indices: Vec<usize>,

    /// One-line summary of the user prompt (first text line, truncated).
    pub user_summary: String,

    /// One-line summary of the agent response (first AgentMessage text line).
    pub agent_summary: String,

    /// Total count of tool calls in the agent response portion.
    pub tool_count: usize,

    /// Total count of file edits in the agent response portion.
    pub edit_count: usize,
}
```

#### 1.3. New fields on `App` struct

```rust
// In the "Session detail state" section of App:
pub detail_view_mode: DetailViewMode,
pub turn_index: usize,            // which turn is selected
pub turn_agent_scroll: u16,       // vertical scroll offset within the agent panel
pub turn_user_scroll: u16,        // vertical scroll offset within the user panel
pub turn_agent_expanded: bool,    // whether agent panel is in expanded/full-detail mode
```

Initialize in `App::new`:
```rust
detail_view_mode: DetailViewMode::Linear,
turn_index: 0,
turn_agent_scroll: 0,
turn_user_scroll: 0,
turn_agent_expanded: false,
```

Reset in `enter_detail`:
```rust
self.detail_view_mode = DetailViewMode::Linear; // or preserve previous choice
self.turn_index = 0;
self.turn_agent_scroll = 0;
self.turn_user_scroll = 0;
self.turn_agent_expanded = false;
```

### 2. Turn Extraction Algorithm

Add this as a method on `App` (or as a free function in `session_detail.rs`):

```rust
/// Extract conversational turns from the visible (filtered) event list.
/// A turn boundary occurs at each UserMessage event.
/// Events before the first UserMessage form "Turn 0" with an empty user side
/// (the preamble/system turn).
fn extract_turns(visible_events: &[DisplayEvent]) -> Vec<Turn> {
    let mut turns: Vec<Turn> = Vec::new();
    let mut current_user_indices: Vec<usize> = Vec::new();
    let mut current_agent_indices: Vec<usize> = Vec::new();
    let mut in_user_block = false;

    for (i, de) in visible_events.iter().enumerate() {
        let event = de.event();
        let is_user = matches!(event.event_type, EventType::UserMessage);

        if is_user {
            // If we have accumulated agent events, finalize the previous turn
            if !current_user_indices.is_empty() || !current_agent_indices.is_empty() {
                turns.push(build_turn(
                    visible_events,
                    &current_user_indices,
                    &current_agent_indices,
                ));
            }
            current_user_indices = vec![i];
            current_agent_indices = Vec::new();
            in_user_block = true;
        } else if in_user_block && matches!(event.event_type, EventType::SystemMessage) {
            // System messages right after user message stay in user column
            current_user_indices.push(i);
        } else {
            in_user_block = false;
            current_agent_indices.push(i);
        }
    }

    // Finalize the last turn
    if !current_user_indices.is_empty() || !current_agent_indices.is_empty() {
        turns.push(build_turn(
            visible_events,
            &current_user_indices,
            &current_agent_indices,
        ));
    }

    turns
}
```

**Key design decisions:**

- **Preamble handling**: If the session starts with agent/system events before any `UserMessage`, those form Turn 0 with an empty left panel. The left panel shows "(system preamble)" or similar placeholder text.
- **Filter interaction**: Turns are extracted from the **already-filtered** `DisplayEvent` list, so filters (1-6 keys) naturally apply. If a filter hides all UserMessages, the entire session collapses into a single turn with an empty user panel.
- **Recomputation**: Turns are recomputed on each render call (they are cheap index vectors). No caching needed since the visible event list is already recomputed each frame.

### 3. Rendering Approach

#### 3.1. Top-level render dispatch in `session_detail::render`

The current `render` function remains mostly unchanged for the header section. After the header, branch on the view mode:

```rust
// After header rendering...
match app.detail_view_mode {
    DetailViewMode::Linear => render_linear_timeline(frame, app, &visible_events, timeline_area),
    DetailViewMode::Turn => render_turn_view(frame, app, &visible_events, timeline_area),
}
```

Extract the current timeline rendering code (lines 148-420 of `session_detail.rs`) into a `render_linear_timeline` function.

#### 3.2. `render_turn_view` layout

```
+------------------------------------------+
| Turn 3/7                      v:linear   |
+-------------------+----------------------+
|  USER             |  AGENT               |
|                   |                       |
|  "Fix the login   |  Think: analyzing... |
|   bug in the      |  Read: src/auth.rs   |
|   auth module"    |  Edit: src/auth.rs   |
|                   |     +3 -1            |
|                   |  Agent: I've fixed   |
|                   |  the authentication  |
|                   |  bug by...           |
|                   |                       |
+-------------------+----------------------+
```

Layout structure:

```rust
fn render_turn_view(
    frame: &mut Frame,
    app: &mut App,
    visible_events: &[DisplayEvent],
    area: Rect,
) {
    let turns = extract_turns(visible_events);
    if turns.is_empty() { /* render empty state */ return; }

    // Clamp turn_index
    let turn_index = app.turn_index.min(turns.len().saturating_sub(1));
    let turn = &turns[turn_index];

    // Title bar with turn counter
    let [title_area, body_area] = Layout::vertical([
        Constraint::Length(1),
        Constraint::Fill(1),
    ]).areas(area);

    // Render turn title: "Turn 3/7  [v:linear]"
    render_turn_title(frame, turn_index, turns.len(), title_area);

    // Split body horizontally
    let panel_split = if app.turn_agent_expanded {
        // Expanded mode: agent gets 80%, user gets 20%
        [Constraint::Percentage(20), Constraint::Percentage(80)]
    } else {
        // Normal mode: roughly equal
        [Constraint::Percentage(40), Constraint::Percentage(60)]
    };
    let [user_area, agent_area] = Layout::horizontal(panel_split).areas(body_area);

    // Render each panel
    render_user_panel(frame, app, visible_events, turn, user_area);
    render_agent_panel(frame, app, visible_events, turn, agent_area);
}
```

#### 3.3. User panel rendering

The user panel shows the user message content with wrapping. Since user messages are typically short, this panel needs:

- A bordered `Block` with title " USER "
- The full text content of the UserMessage event(s), rendered via `render_content_preview` (reusing the existing function) but with a higher `max_lines` limit (e.g., 50)
- Its own scroll state (`turn_user_scroll`) if the content overflows
- A scrollbar if needed

```rust
fn render_user_panel(
    frame: &mut Frame,
    app: &App,
    visible_events: &[DisplayEvent],
    turn: &Turn,
    area: Rect,
) {
    let block = Block::bordered()
        .title(" USER ")
        .title_style(Style::new().fg(Color::Rgb(80, 180, 100)).bold())
        .border_style(Style::new().fg(Color::Rgb(60, 65, 80)));

    if turn.user_event_indices.is_empty() {
        // Preamble turn -- no user message
        let p = Paragraph::new(Span::styled(
            "(system preamble)",
            Style::new().fg(Color::DarkGray).italic(),
        ))
        .block(block);
        frame.render_widget(p, area);
        return;
    }

    // Build lines from user events
    let mut lines: Vec<Line> = Vec::new();
    for &idx in &turn.user_event_indices {
        let event = visible_events[idx].event();
        render_content_preview(
            &event.content.blocks,
            &mut lines,
            area.width.saturating_sub(4) as usize,
            50, // generous max_lines for user content
        );
    }

    let p = Paragraph::new(lines)
        .block(block)
        .wrap(Wrap { trim: false })
        .scroll((app.turn_user_scroll, 0));
    frame.render_widget(p, area);
}
```

#### 3.4. Agent panel rendering

The agent panel is richer. It should show a condensed summary of all agent-side events, similar to the linear view but without the selection pointer.

Two rendering modes depending on `turn_agent_expanded`:

**Normal mode** (default): Show a condensed list -- each event as a one-line summary (type label + summary text), using the existing `event_type_display` and `event_summary` functions. This gives a quick overview.

**Expanded mode** (Enter/Space toggle): Show full content previews for all events, similar to the linear view with `should_expand = true` for all events.

```rust
fn render_agent_panel(
    frame: &mut Frame,
    app: &App,
    visible_events: &[DisplayEvent],
    turn: &Turn,
    area: Rect,
) {
    let title = if app.turn_agent_expanded {
        " AGENT (expanded) "
    } else {
        " AGENT "
    };
    let block = Block::bordered()
        .title(title)
        .title_style(Style::new().fg(Color::Rgb(100, 140, 220)).bold())
        .border_style(Style::new().fg(Color::Rgb(60, 65, 80)));

    let inner_width = area.width.saturating_sub(4) as usize;
    let mut lines: Vec<Line> = Vec::new();

    for &idx in &turn.agent_event_indices {
        let de = &visible_events[idx];
        let event = de.event();
        let (type_label, type_color) = event_type_display(&event.event_type);
        let summary = event_summary(&event.event_type, &event.content.blocks);

        // One-line summary for each event
        lines.push(Line::from(vec![
            Span::styled("│ ", Style::new().fg(type_color)),
            Span::styled(
                format!("{:<6}", type_label),
                Style::new().fg(type_color).bold(),
            ),
            Span::raw(" "),
            Span::styled(summary, Style::new().fg(Color::White)),
        ]));

        // In expanded mode, show content preview for rich events
        if app.turn_agent_expanded {
            let max_lines = 20;
            if let EventType::FileEdit { diff: Some(ref d), .. } = &event.event_type {
                render_diff_preview(d, &mut lines, max_lines);
            } else if matches!(
                event.event_type,
                EventType::AgentMessage | EventType::Thinking
            ) {
                render_content_preview(
                    &event.content.blocks,
                    &mut lines,
                    inner_width,
                    max_lines,
                );
            }
        }
    }

    // Handle sub-agent tasks: TaskSummary events render inline
    // (they already carry summary text from the DisplayEvent)

    if lines.is_empty() {
        lines.push(Line::from(Span::styled(
            "(no agent events)",
            Style::new().fg(Color::DarkGray),
        )));
    }

    let visible_height = area.height.saturating_sub(2) as usize;
    let total_lines = lines.len();

    let p = Paragraph::new(lines)
        .block(block)
        .wrap(Wrap { trim: false })
        .scroll((app.turn_agent_scroll, 0));
    frame.render_widget(p, area);

    // Scrollbar for agent panel
    if total_lines > visible_height {
        let mut scrollbar_state = ScrollbarState::new(total_lines)
            .position(app.turn_agent_scroll as usize);
        let scrollbar = Scrollbar::new(ScrollbarOrientation::VerticalRight)
            .begin_symbol(None)
            .end_symbol(None)
            .thumb_style(Style::new().fg(Color::Rgb(80, 85, 100)));
        frame.render_stateful_widget(
            scrollbar,
            area.inner(Margin { vertical: 1, horizontal: 0 }),
            &mut scrollbar_state,
        );
    }
}
```

#### 3.5. Sub-agent task handling

Sub-agent tasks (TaskStart/TaskEnd and their inner events) should follow the same `task_view_mode` behavior as the linear view:

- In `TaskViewMode::Summary`: TaskSummary `DisplayEvent` variants appear as single lines in the agent panel with a distinct TASK label and event count.
- In `TaskViewMode::Detail`: All inner events appear individually, potentially with tree-prefix indentation. Reuse the same tree-prefix logic from the linear renderer.

This works naturally because `extract_turns` operates on the already-processed `DisplayEvent` list (which has already had `apply_task_view_mode` applied).

### 4. State Management

#### 4.1. Turn navigation (j/k in Turn mode)

When `detail_view_mode == DetailViewMode::Turn`:
- `j`/`Down`: increment `turn_index` (clamped to `turns.len() - 1`), reset `turn_agent_scroll` and `turn_user_scroll` to 0
- `k`/`Up`: decrement `turn_index`, reset scrolls
- `G`/`End`: jump to last turn
- `g`/`Home`: jump to first turn

#### 4.2. Intra-panel scroll (agent panel overflow)

Since the agent panel can have many events, provide scroll within the panel:
- `Ctrl+d` / `Ctrl+u`: scroll the agent panel down/up by half-page
- Or simpler: arrow keys for single-line scroll, PageDown/PageUp for page scroll (but this conflicts with turn navigation)

**Proposed approach**: In Turn mode, `j`/`k` navigate turns. For scrolling within the agent panel, use:
- `J` (shift-j) or `Ctrl+d`: scroll agent panel down
- `K` (shift-k) or `Ctrl+u`: scroll agent panel up
- This avoids conflict with `j`/`k` for turn navigation

Actually, looking at the existing code, `G` and `g` are already used. A cleaner approach:

- `j`/`k`: navigate between turns
- `PageDown`/`PageUp`: scroll agent panel content
- `Enter`/`Space`: toggle agent panel expanded mode
- `Ctrl+j`/`Ctrl+k` or simply allow the user panel to auto-fit (user messages are usually short enough to fit)

#### 4.3. Expanded mode toggle

`Enter` or `Space` in Turn mode toggles `turn_agent_expanded`. When toggled:
- The horizontal split changes from 40/60 to 20/80
- Agent panel shows full content previews
- Agent panel scroll resets to 0

### 5. Key Handling Changes

Modify `handle_detail_key` in `app.rs`:

```rust
fn handle_detail_key(&mut self, key: KeyCode) -> bool {
    match key {
        // View mode toggle: 'v' switches Linear <-> Turn
        KeyCode::Char('v') => {
            self.detail_view_mode = match self.detail_view_mode {
                DetailViewMode::Linear => {
                    // Entering Turn mode: find which turn contains the
                    // currently selected event and set turn_index accordingly
                    self.turn_agent_scroll = 0;
                    self.turn_user_scroll = 0;
                    self.turn_agent_expanded = false;
                    // (compute initial turn_index from detail_event_index)
                    DetailViewMode::Turn
                }
                DetailViewMode::Turn => {
                    // Returning to Linear: set detail_event_index to the
                    // first event of the current turn
                    DetailViewMode::Linear
                }
            };
            return false;
        }

        // Back/quit -- same for both modes
        KeyCode::Char('q') | KeyCode::Esc | KeyCode::Char('h') | KeyCode::Left => {
            self.view = View::SessionList;
            self.detail_scroll = 0;
            self.detail_event_index = 0;
            self.detail_view_mode = DetailViewMode::Linear;
        }

        // Mode-specific navigation
        _ => {
            match self.detail_view_mode {
                DetailViewMode::Linear => self.handle_linear_detail_key(key),
                DetailViewMode::Turn => self.handle_turn_detail_key(key),
            }
        }
    }
    false
}

fn handle_turn_detail_key(&mut self, key: KeyCode) {
    match key {
        // Turn navigation
        KeyCode::Char('j') | KeyCode::Down => self.turn_next(),
        KeyCode::Char('k') | KeyCode::Up => self.turn_prev(),
        KeyCode::Char('G') | KeyCode::End => self.turn_end(),
        KeyCode::Char('g') | KeyCode::Home => {
            self.turn_index = 0;
            self.turn_agent_scroll = 0;
        }

        // Agent panel scroll
        KeyCode::PageDown => {
            self.turn_agent_scroll = self.turn_agent_scroll.saturating_add(10);
        }
        KeyCode::PageUp => {
            self.turn_agent_scroll = self.turn_agent_scroll.saturating_sub(10);
        }

        // Expand/collapse agent panel
        KeyCode::Enter | KeyCode::Char(' ') => {
            self.turn_agent_expanded = !self.turn_agent_expanded;
            self.turn_agent_scroll = 0;
        }

        // Filters still work in Turn mode
        KeyCode::Char('1') => self.toggle_event_filter(EventFilter::All),
        KeyCode::Char('2') => self.toggle_event_filter(EventFilter::Messages),
        KeyCode::Char('3') => self.toggle_event_filter(EventFilter::ToolCalls),
        KeyCode::Char('4') => self.toggle_event_filter(EventFilter::Thinking),
        KeyCode::Char('5') => self.toggle_event_filter(EventFilter::FileOps),
        KeyCode::Char('6') => self.toggle_event_filter(EventFilter::Shell),

        // Task view mode toggle
        KeyCode::Char('t') => self.toggle_task_view_mode(),
        KeyCode::Char('c') => {
            self.collapse_consecutive = !self.collapse_consecutive;
            self.turn_index = 0;
        }

        // u/U still jump between turns (since each turn starts with a user message)
        KeyCode::Char('u') => self.turn_next(),
        KeyCode::Char('U') => self.turn_prev(),

        _ => {}
    }
}
```

Turn navigation helpers:

```rust
fn turn_next(&mut self) {
    // We need the turn count; since we can't easily compute it here
    // without the session, we'll use a reasonable upper bound and
    // clamp during rendering. Or, store computed turn_count.
    self.turn_index = self.turn_index.saturating_add(1);
    self.turn_agent_scroll = 0;
    self.turn_user_scroll = 0;
}

fn turn_prev(&mut self) {
    self.turn_index = self.turn_index.saturating_sub(1);
    self.turn_agent_scroll = 0;
    self.turn_user_scroll = 0;
}

fn turn_end(&mut self) {
    // Set to usize::MAX; renderer will clamp
    self.turn_index = usize::MAX;
    self.turn_agent_scroll = 0;
}
```

### 6. Header/Footer UI Changes

#### 6.1. Header bar (in `ui.rs`, `View::SessionDetail` branch)

Add a view mode indicator alongside the existing filter badges:

